[normal]The 
[normal]Crown Estate welcomes the
[normal] 
[normal]opportunity to respond to 
[normal]t
[normal]he Scottish Affairs Committee’s consultation on land reform in Scotland. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2 
[normal]As a landowner and as the manager of a diverse portfolio 
[normal]across the UK
[normal], our experience enables us to offer insights which may help to inform the debate.
[normal] We responded to the Scottish Government’s Land Reform Review Group Call for Evidence in January 2013
[normal] and met with the Group in September 2013.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3 
[normal]It would no
[normal]t be appropriate for us to take a political view on the 
[normal]wide ranging
[normal] public policy 
[normal]issues 
[normal]outlined in the Terms of Reference and 
[normal]discussed in the briefing paper “
[normal]432:50 – Towards a comprehensive land reform agenda for Scotland
[normal]”, but we hope that the commen
[normal]ts below are useful in informing the Committee’s deliberations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4 
[normal]It is important to note that th
[normal]is submission is written in the context of 
[normal]The Government response to the seventh report of the Scottish Affairs Committee session 2010-12 on The Crown 
[normal]Estate in Scotland
[normal],
[normal] i
[normal]n 
[normal]which
[normal] the UK Government rejected 
[normal]recommendations
[normal] to devolve The Crown Estate 
[normal]assets.
