[normal]3. [bold]The[bold] land reform agenda[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1 
[normal]While we acknowledge the 
[normal]success of the community land ownership initiatives which have taken place in Scotland, 
[normal]our experience indicates that many of the benefits that could accrue can also be achieved by other mechanisms which enhance the opportunities for tenants an
[normal]d communitie
[normal]s to shape how land 
[normal]is managed. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2 
[normal]In this respect
[normal],
[normal] the
[normal] Committee’s
[normal] 
[normal]briefing 
[normal]paper
[normal] largely confines 
[normal]consideration of 
[normal]land reform to the transfer of ownership. While there may be merits to this in many cases
[normal],
[normal] it is equally true that many tenant farmers d
[normal]o not find ownership attractive. Indeed, the STFA survey referred to in the report states 
[normal]that 
[normal]80% of respondents believed rural communities would benefit from ‘greater diversity of ownership’ rather than simply land transfer. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3 
[normal]The Crown Estate works 
[normal]in close partnership with communities (through development trusts, liaison groups etc.
[normal],) in a way that empowers them 
[normal]without them having to take on the liabilities
[normal] 
[normal]associated with ownership. The 
[normal]Scotland’s
[normal] Rural College 
[normal]makes this point i
[normal]n their respons
[normal]e 
[normal]to the Scottish Government’s Land Reform R
[normal]eview
[normal] Group
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4 
[normal]"While there are many examples of successful community landowners in the Highlands and Islands, 
[normal]it is not a panacea and success is never easy, requiring a great deal of
[normal] sustained effort by all sta
[normal]keholders. There are instances where close partnership working between landowners and rural 
[normal]communities brings significant mutual benefits, and avoids the responsibilities and costs for communities of owning the land."
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.5 
[normal]This is echoed in a report for 
[normal]the Big Lottery, Growing Community Assets Evaluation (Final Year Report).
[normal] 
[normal] SCDI, in their response 
[normal]to
[normal] the Scottish 
[normal]Government’s
[normal] Land R
[normal]e
[normal]f
[normal]orm Re
[normal]view Group, 
[normal]indicate the relative importance of factors other than land 
[normal]ownership
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.6 
[normal]“
[normal]SCDI understands that, 
[normal]in some cases, ownership of land is a central factor in economic growth, particularly where an owner is a barrier to development or fails to maintain their land holding. SCDI recognises the benefits that community ownership can have on fragile communities 
[normal]as has been demonstrated with both 
[normal]Gigha
[normal] and 
[normal]Eigg
[normal]. However; in most cases the ownership of land is secondary to the impact of factors such as the economic climate, government legislative measures, taxation or other policy leavers, and the lack of discussio
[normal]n over land use
[normal].”
[normal]3.7 
[normal]For this reason
[normal] it will be just as important to ensure that estates pursue good practice i
[normal]n terms of both integrated land-use and 
[normal]giving tenants and communities a stake in their 
[normal]land
[normal], within the broader context of sustainable economi
[normal]c development
[normal].
[normal] 
