[normal]4. [bold]Our work with rural &amp; coastal communities[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1 
[normal]From the perspective of The Crown Estate, there are three strands of our work which 
[normal]relate to issues raised in the Committee’s briefing paper.
[normal] These include:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4.2 
[normal]We would suggest that some of the ways in which we
[normal] [bold]enable tenants and communities to manage land and foreshore across 
[normal]our 
[normal]rural and coastal estates may offer models for other landowners. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4.3 
[normal]These range from structuring leases to meet the stated desire of a community for direct management and control, supporting locally-run organisations to manage assets, a
[normal]nd our 
[normal]Local Management Agreements
[normal],
[normal] an 
[normal]initiative
[normal] 
[normal]introduced in 2012 following the C
[normal]ommittee’s
[normal] inquiry into The Crown Estate. LMAs
[normal] empower communities to manage areas of the foreshore.
[normal] 
[normal]Below we provide examples and 
[normal]outline
[normal] the benefits that these initiatives have delivered. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4 [bold]Local Management Agreements (LMA[bold]s[bold])[bold]&#xa0;
